`w i = 1/s.card`
Then `∑_{j ∈ s} w j = ∑_{j ∈ s} 1/s.card = s.card * (1/s.card) = 1`.

Now we need to show `(s \ {i}).centerMass w x = y i`. The center of mass is `∑_{j ∈ s \ {i}} w j x j`. With `w j = 1/s.card`, this is `∑_{j ∈ s \ {i}} (1/s.card) x j = (1/s.card) * ∑_{j ∈ s \ {i}} x j`.
This is `(1/s.card) * (s.card - 1) * x i + ...` which doesn't seem right.

Let's think differently. We need `y i = ∑_{j ∈ s \ {i}} w j x j` with `∑ w j = 1` and `w j ≥ 0`. This is exactly the definition of `y i` being in the convex hull of `x j` for `j ∈ s \ {i}`.

